1 SECTION 15. IC 16-34-7 IS ADDED TO THE INDIANA CODE
2 AS A NEW CHAPTER TO READ AS FOLLOWS [EFFECTIVE
3 JULY 1, 2026]:
4 Chapter 7. Abortion Inducing Drugs
5 Sec. 1. (a) This chapter does not apply to and a civil action
6 under this chapter may not be brought against:
7 (1) a hospital or health facility licensed, owned, maintained,
8 or operated by the state;
9 (2) a physician or health care provider who is:
10 (A) licensed by the state; and
11 (B) located in Indiana;
12 (3) an Internet service provider or an affiliate of subsidiary of
13 an Internet service provider;
14 (4) an Internet service engine;
15 (5) a cloud service provider providing access or connection to
16 or from:
17 (A) a website;
18 (B) other information or content on the Internet;
19 (C) a facility, system, or network that is not under the
20 provider's control, including:
21 (i) transmission;
22 (ii) downloading;
23 (iii) intermediate storage; or
24 (iv) access software.
25 (b) This chapter does not apply to the transport of an abortion
26 inducing drug from a person in another state in continuous transit
27 through Indiana to a person in another state.
28 Sec. 2. This chapter may not be construed to require the actual
29 performance, inducement, or attempted performance of an
30 abortion in order for a person to bring a civil action under this
31 chapter.
32 Sec. 3. The following definitions apply throughout this chapter:
33 (1) "Delivery network company" has the meaning set forth in
34 IC 8-2.1-17-5.3.
35 (2) "DNC driver" has the meaning set forth in IC 8-2.1-17-5.7.
36 (3) "Health facility" means a building, a structure, an
37 institution, or other place for the reception, accommodation,
38 board, care, or treatment extending beyond a continuous
39 twenty-four (24) hour period in a week of more than four (4)
40 individuals who need or desire such services because of
41 physical or mental illness, infirmity, or impairment. The term
42 does not include a hospital.
2026 IN 236—LS 7104/DI 107

21
1 (4) "Physician" means an individual licensed to practice
2 medicine in Indiana, include a medical doctor and a doctor of
3 osteopathic medicine.
4 Sec. 4. (a) Except as provided by subsection (b), a person may
5 not knowingly or intentionally:
6 (1) manufacture, distribute, or possess an abortion inducing
7 drug; or
8 (2) mail, transport, deliver, prescribe, or provide an abortion
9 inducing drug in any manner to or from any person or
10 location in Indiana.
11 (b) Subsection (a) does not prohibit:
12 (1) speech or conduct protected by the First Amendment to
13 the Constitution of the United States, as made applicable to
14 the states through the United States Supreme Court's
15 interpretation of the Fourteenth Amendment to the
16 Constitution of the United States, or protected by Article 1,
17 Section 9 of the Constitution of the State of Indiana;
18 (2) conduct that a pregnant woman takes in the course of
19 aborting or attempting to abort the woman's unborn child;
20 (3) the manufacture, distribution, mailing, transport, delivery,
21 prescribing, provision, or possession of an abortion inducing
22 drug solely for purposes that do not include performing,
23 inducing, attempting, assisting, or aiding or abetting an illegal
24 abortion; or
25 (4) conduct that a person takes under the direction of a
26 federal agency, contractor, or employee to carry out a duty
27 under federal law, if prohibiting that conduct would violate
28 the doctrine of preemption or intergovernmental immunity.
29 Sec. 5. (a) Notwithstanding any other law, the prohibitions in
30 section 4 of this chapter may be enforced only through a wrongful
31 death action brought under section 4 of this chapter or a qui tam
32 action brought under section 9 of this chapter.
33 (b) No other direct or indirect enforcement of section 4 of this
34 chapter may be taken or threatened by:
35 (1) the State of Indiana;
36 (2) a political subdivision of the state;
37 (3) a prosecuting attorney;
38 (4) a county attorney;
39 (5) any officer or employee of the state; or
40 (6) any officer or employee of a political subdivision of the
41 state;
42 against any person, except through a wrongful death action
2026 IN 236—LS 7104/DI 107

22
1 brought under section 4 of this chapter or a qui tam action brought
2 under section 9 of this chapter.
3 (c) This section does not preclude or limit the enforcement of
4 any other law or regulation against conduct that is independently
5 prohibited by the other law or regulation and that would remain
6 prohibited by the other law or regulation in the absence of section
7 4 of this chapter.
8 Sec. 6. (a) Notwithstanding any other law, and except as
9 provided in subsections (b) and (f), a person who manufactures,
10 distributes, mails, transports, delivers, prescribes, or provides an
11 abortion inducing drug, or who aids or abets the manufacture,
12 distribution, mailing, transportation, delivery, prescription, or
13 provision of an abortion inducing drug, is strictly, absolutely, and
14 jointly and severally liable for:
15 (1) the wrongful death of an unborn child or pregnant woman
16 from the use of the abortion inducing drug; and
17 (2) personal injury of an unborn child or pregnant woman
18 from the use of the abortion inducing drug.
19 (b) A claimant may not bring an action under this section if the
20 action is preempted by 47 U.S.C. 230(c).
21 (c) A person who engages in conduct described by subsection (a)
22 is liable for damages resulting from the death or personal injury
23 sustained by an unborn child or pregnant woman if the person's
24 conduct contributed in any way to the death or injury, regardless
25 of whether the person's conduct was the actual or proximate cause
26 of the death or injury.
27 (d) Notwithstanding any other law, the mother or father of an
28 unborn child may bring a civil action under this section for the
29 wrongful death of the unborn child from the use of an abortion
30 inducing drug, regardless of whether the other parent brings a civil
31 action for the wrongful death. The biological father of an unborn
32 child may bring the action regardless of whether the father was
33 married to the unborn child's mother at the time of the unborn
34 child's conception or death.
35 (e) Notwithstanding any other law, a civil action may not be
36 brought under this section:
37 (1) against the woman who used or sought to obtain abortion
38 inducing drugs to abort or attempt to abort her unborn child;
39 (2) against a person that acted under the direction of a federal
40 agency, contractor, or employee who is carrying out duties
41 under federal law if the imposition of liability would violate
42 the doctrine of preemption or intergovernmental immunity;
2026 IN 236—LS 7104/DI 107

23
1 (3) by any person who has committed a sex crime as defined
2 in IC 35-42-4, or by another person who acts in concert or
3 participation with such a person;
